#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:3
msgid "Integration testing with NixOS virtual machines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:5
msgid "What will you learn?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:7
msgid ""
"This tutorial introduces Nixpkgs functionality for testing NixOS "
"configurations. It also shows how to set up distributed test scenarios that "
"involve multiple machines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:10
msgid "What do you need?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:12
msgid ""
"A working [Nix installation](<install-nix>) on Linux, or [NixOS](https://"
"nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#sec-installation)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:13
msgid "Basic knowledge of the [Nix language](<reading-nix-language>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:14
msgid "Basic knowledge of [NixOS configuration](<nixos-vms>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:16
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:18
msgid ""
"Nixpkgs provides a [test environment](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/"
"index.html#sec-nixos-tests) to automate integration testing for distributed "
"systems. It allows defining tests based on a set of declarative NixOS "
"configurations and using a Python shell to interact with them through [QEMU]"
"(https://www.qemu.org/) as the backend. Those tests are widely used to "
"ensure that NixOS works as intended, so in general they are called [NixOS "
"Tests](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#sec-nixos-tests). "
"They can be written and launched outside of NixOS, on any Linux "
"machine[^darwin]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:25
msgid ""
"Integration tests are reproducible due to the design properties of Nix, "
"making them a valuable part of a continuous integration (CI) pipeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:27
msgid "The `testers.runNixOSTest` function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:29
msgid ""
"NixOS VM tests are defined using the `testers.runNixOSTest` function. The "
"pattern for NixOS VM tests looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:32
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-23.11\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
"\n"
"pkgs.testers.runNixOSTest {\n"
"  name = \"test-name\";\n"
"  nodes = {\n"
"    machine1 = { config, pkgs, ... }: {\n"
"      # ...\n"
"    };\n"
"    machine2 = { config, pkgs, ... }: {\n"
"      # ...\n"
"    };\n"
"  };\n"
"  testScript = { nodes, ... }: ''\n"
"    # ...\n"
"  '';\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:54
msgid ""
"The function `testers.runNixOSTest` takes a [module](https://nixos.org/"
"manual/nixos/stable/#sec-writing-modules) to specify the [test options]"
"(https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#sec-test-options-"
"reference). Because this module only sets configuration values, one can use "
"the abbreviated module notation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:57
msgid "The following configuration values must be set:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:59
msgid ""
"[`name`](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#test-opt-name) "
"defines the name of the test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:61
msgid ""
"[`nodes`](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#test-opt-nodes) "
"contains a set of named configurations, because a test script can involve "
"more than one virtual machine. Each virtual machine is created from a NixOS "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:64
msgid ""
"[`testScript`](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#test-opt-"
"testScript) defines the Python test script, either as literal string or as a "
"function that takes a `nodes` attribute. This Python test script can access "
"the virtual machines via the names used for the `nodes`. It has super user "
"rights in the virtual machines. In the Python script each virtual machine is "
"accessible via the `machine` object. NixOS provides [various methods]"
"(https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/index.html#ssec-machine-objects) to "
"run tests on these configurations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:70
msgid ""
"The test framework automatically starts the virtual machines and runs the "
"Python script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:72
msgid "Minimal example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:74
msgid ""
"As a minimal test on the default configuration, we will check if the user "
"`root` and `alice` can run Firefox. We will build the example up from "
"scratch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:77
msgid ""
"Use a [pinned version of Nixpkgs](ref-pinning-nixpkgs), and [explicitly set "
"configuration options and overlays](nixpkgs-config) to avoid them being "
"inadvertently overridden by global configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:79
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-23.11\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
"\n"
"pkgs.testers.runNixOSTest {\n"
"  # ...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:90
msgid "Label the test with a descriptive name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:92
msgid "name = \"minimal-test\";\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:96
msgid ""
"Because this example only uses one virtual machine, the node we specify is "
"simply called `machine`. This name is arbitrary and can be chosen freely. As "
"configuration you use the relevant parts of the default configuration, "
"[which we used in a previous tutorial](<nixos-vms>):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:100
msgid ""
"nodes.machine = { config, pkgs, ... }: {\n"
"  users.users.alice = {\n"
"    isNormalUser = true;\n"
"    extraGroups = [ \"wheel\" ];\n"
"    packages = with pkgs; [\n"
"      firefox\n"
"      tree\n"
"    ];\n"
"  };\n"
"\n"
"  system.stateVersion = \"23.11\";\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:115
msgid "This is the test script:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:117
msgid ""
"machine.wait_for_unit(\"default.target\")\n"
"machine.succeed(\"su -- alice -c 'which firefox'\")\n"
"machine.fail(\"su -- root -c 'which firefox'\")\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:123
msgid ""
"This Python script refers to `machine` which is the name chosen for the "
"virtual machine configuration used in the `nodes` attribute set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:125
msgid ""
"The script waits until systemd reaches `default.target`. It uses the `su` "
"command to switch between users and the `which` command to check if the user "
"has access to `firefox`. It expects that the command `which firefox` to "
"succeed for user `alice` and to fail for `root`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:129
msgid "This script will be the value of the `testScript` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:131
msgid "The complete `minimal-test.nix` file content looks like the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:133
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  nixpkgs = fetchTarball \"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/"
"nixos-23.11\";\n"
"  pkgs = import nixpkgs { config = {}; overlays = []; };\n"
"in\n"
"\n"
"pkgs.testers.runNixOSTest {\n"
"  name = \"minimal-test\";\n"
"\n"
"  nodes.machine = { config, pkgs, ... }: {\n"
"\n"
"    users.users.alice = {\n"
"      isNormalUser = true;\n"
"      extraGroups = [ \"wheel\" ];\n"
"      packages = with pkgs; [\n"
"        firefox\n"
"        tree\n"
"      ];\n"
"    };\n"
"\n"
"    system.stateVersion = \"23.11\";\n"
"  };\n"
"\n"
"  testScript = ''\n"
"    machine.wait_for_unit(\"default.target\")\n"
"    machine.succeed(\"su -- alice -c 'which firefox'\")\n"
"    machine.fail(\"su -- root -c 'which firefox'\")\n"
"  '';\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:164
msgid "Running tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:166
msgid "To set up all machines and run the test script:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/nixos/integration-testing-using-virtual-machines.md:168
msgid "$ nix-build minimal-test.nix\n"
msgstr ""

